<subSubSection id="0AAD2DB5FF99214CFEC987864068FB3A" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="42087E3EFF99214CFEC98786409DFBF0" blockId="1.[278,924,1008,1070]" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">
<heading id="1940C952FF99214CFEC98786409DFBF0" bold="true" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" reason="2">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF99214CFEC98786409DFBF0" bold="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFEC9878640F0FBD5" authority=", Euzygentoma" authorityName="Euzygentoma" box="[278,661,1009,1035]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Archaeognatha, Euzygentoma</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFD3F878741F7FBD5" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[736,914,1008,1035]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF99214CFD3F878741F7FBD5" bold="true" box="[736,914,1008,1035]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: one more insect ‘order’?
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="42087E3EFF99214CFF4F803A4068FB3A" blockId="1.[113,1090,1100,1573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">
As both groups of the primarily wingless true insects, the bristletails (
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFCB6803B466BFBBA" box="[873,1038,1100,1124]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Archaeognatha</taxonomicName>
) and the silverfish (
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFEDA801B43E1FB5A" box="[261,388,1132,1156]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Zygentoma</taxonomicName>
), are superficially similar morphologically, they were united in one group (‘Thysanura’). It has long been known, however, that the bristletails are in general more basal and that the silverfish are more closely related to the winged insects (together forming the Dicondylia) than to the bristletails.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0AAD2DB5FF99214FFF4F809A463EFE2D" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="219" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" type="description">
<paragraph id="42087E3EFF99214FFF4F809A463EFE2D" blockId="1.[113,1090,1100,1573]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1127,219,1588]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="219" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">
It may be that things are not that simple. The apparently primitive zygentoman family 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFFAE817B437FFAFA" box="[113,282,1292,1316]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lepidotrichidae</taxonomicName>
was originally described from the mid-Eocene Baltic amber genus 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFC3981794340FA9A" authority="Menge, 1854" authorityName="Menge" authorityYear="1854" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Lepidotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF99214CFC39817942EAFA9B" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">Lepidotrix</emphasis>
Menge, 1854
</taxonomicName>
, and is now represented by a single living species, 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFC9881594322FABA" authority="Wygodzinsky, 1961" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gertschi">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF99214CFC9881594624FA9B" box="[839,1089,1326,1349]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">Tricholepidion gertschi</emphasis>
Wygodzinsky, 1961
</taxonomicName>
, from northern California. The family 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFD3F813B41ECFABA" box="[736,905,1356,1380]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lepidotrichidae</taxonomicName>
itself may not be monophyletic, since 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFE90811940A0FA5A" authority="Wygodzinsky, 1961" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[335,709,1388,1413]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF99214CFE9081194389FA5B" box="[335,492,1390,1413]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
Wygodzinsky, 1961
</taxonomicName>
(the only zygentoman with distinct ocelli) may be more primitive than 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFE2E81F94005FA7B" authorityName="Menge" authorityYear="1854" box="[497,608,1422,1445]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Lepidotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF99214CFE2E81F94005FA7B" box="[497,608,1422,1445]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">Lepidotrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and less closely related to the Euzygentoma (= 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFF4E81DB4376FA1A" authorityName="Escherich" authorityYear="1905" box="[145,275,1452,1476]" class="Insecta" family="Nicoletiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Nicoletiidae</taxonomicName>
s. lat. + 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFEAD81DB4067FA1A" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[370,514,1452,1476]" class="Insecta" family="Lepismatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lepismatidae</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFDFF81DB40A7FA1A" authorityName="Escherich" authorityYear="1905" box="[544,706,1452,1476]" class="Insecta" family="Maindroniidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Maindroniidae</taxonomicName>
). The 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFCDB81DB41C8FA1A" box="[772,941,1452,1476]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lepidotrichidae</taxonomicName>
possess large abdominal sterna with posteriorly attached coxopodites, and a large number of pregenital abdominal styli and eversible sacs. Five characters have been proposed to support intrazygentoman position of 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF99214CFEB382794062F9FB" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[364,519,1550,1573]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF99214CFEB382794062F9FB" box="[364,519,1550,1573]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="218">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF99214CFDE4827B4122F9FA" author="GRIMALDI D. &amp; ENGEL M. S." box="[571,839,1548,1572]" pageId="1" pageNumber="218" refId="ref8835" refString="GRIMALDI D. &amp; ENGEL M. S. 2005: Evolution of the Insects. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, xv + 755 pp." type="book" year="2005">GRIMALDI &amp; ENGEL (2005)</bibRefCitation>
and references therein). They include (i) unique sensillar structures on the terminal filament (shared by 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFC1584AA4603FF2A" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[970,1126,221,244]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFC1584AA4603FF2A" box="[970,1126,221,244]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFF35848C4314FECD" authorityName="Escherich" authorityYear="1905" box="[234,369,251,275]" class="Insecta" family="Nicoletiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Nicoletiidae</taxonomicName>
), (ii) a widened apical segment of the labial palp, (iii) obliteration of the superlingua, (iv) mating behaviour (the male deposits a spermatophore on a web which he has spun during the final phase of foreplay; the female picks up the spermatophore using her ovipositor; see 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFEE8852B43B1FEAA" author="STURM H." box="[311,468,348,372]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="44 - 49" refId="ref10245" refString="STURM H. 1997: The mating behaviour of Tricholepidion gertschi Wygod., 1961 (Lepidotrichidae, Zygentoma) and its comparison with the behaviour of other &quot; Apterygota &quot;. Pedobiologia 41: 44 - 49." type="journal article" year="1997">STURM (1997))</bibRefCitation>
, and (v) sperm conjugation (putatively shared by 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFC04852A42D7FE4A" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFC04852A42D7FE4A" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFED0850C43C1FE4D" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[271,420,379,403]" class="Insecta" family="Lepismatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lepismatidae</taxonomicName>
). However, even in the nicoletiids (
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFCFE850A4677FE4D" authority="Heyden, 1855" authorityName="Heyden" authorityYear="1855" box="[801,1042,379,404]" class="Insecta" family="Nicoletiidae" genus="Atelura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFCFE850A4114FE4A" box="[801,881,381,404]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Atelura</emphasis>
Heyden, 1855
</taxonomicName>
), sperm bundles are stored in the proximal part of the testes, intermingled with dense granules and forming the so called ‘spermatolophids’. Sperm aggregation in the 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFCBE85CB41BFFE0A" box="[865,986,444,468]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Zygentoma</taxonomicName>
is, therefore, quite diverse (
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFEF085AB4064FE2D" author="DALLAI R. &amp; LUPETTI P. &amp; FRATI F. &amp; NARDI F. &amp; AFZELIUS B. A." box="[303,513,475,500]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="606 - 613" refId="ref8463" refString="DALLAI R., LUPETTI P., FRATI F., NARDI F. &amp; AFZELIUS B. A. 2001 a: Binucleate and biflagellate spermatozoa in Tricholepidion gertschi Wygodzinsky (Insecta, Zygentoma). Tissue &amp; Cell 33: 606 - 613." type="journal article" year="2001">DALLAI et al. 2001a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFDDA85AC4033FE2A" author="SIMICZYJEW B." box="[517,598,475,500]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="61 - 66" refId="ref10135" refString="SIMICZYJEW B. 2002: Structure of the ovary in Nannochorista neotropica Navas (Insecta: Mecoptera: Nannochoristidae) with remarks on mecopteran phylogeny. Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 83: 61 - 66." type="journal article" year="2002">b, 2002</bibRefCitation>
) and its phylogenetic interpretation is uncertain.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0AAD2DB5FF9A214FFF6A858A40ECFB8D" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="42087E3EFF9A214FFF6A858A408BFD0A" blockId="2.[151,1127,219,1588]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFF6A858A4335FDCA" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[181,336,509,532]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFF6A858A4335FDCA" box="[181,336,509,532]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has five-segmented tarsi, which is the presumed plesiomorphic condition for Pterygota, while both the 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFE7E866C4027FDED" box="[417,578,539,563]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Archaeognatha</taxonomicName>
and the Euzygentoma have two- or three-segmented tarsi. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFE93864A438CFD8A" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[332,489,573,596]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFE93864A438CFD8A" box="[332,489,573,596]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ovaries are clearly primitive and archaeognath-like, being composed of seven metamerically arranged ovarioles (compare three or five non-metameric ovarioles in the Euzygentoma and the highly variable number and arrangement of ovarioles but no ovary metamerism in the Pterygota; 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFDB886EC4174FD6A" author="STYS P. &amp; ZRZAVY J. &amp; WEYDA F." box="[615,785,667,692]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="365 - 379" refId="ref10316" refString="STYS P., ZRZAVY J. &amp; WEYDA F. 1993: Phylogeny of the Hexapoda and ovarian metamerism. Biological Reviews of the Cambridge Philosophical Society 68: 365 - 379." type="journal article" year="1993">ŠTYS et al. 1993</bibRefCitation>
) and including opaque granules in early vitellogenic oocytes (
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFE0B86CB4086FD0A" author="SZKLARZEWICZ T. &amp; JABLONSKA A. &amp; BILINSKI S. M." box="[468,739,699,724]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="477 - 485" refId="ref10350" refString="SZKLARZEWICZ T., JABLONSKA A. &amp; BILINSKI S. M. 2004: Ovaries of Petrobius brevistylis (Archaeognatha, Machilidae) and Tricholepidion gertschi (Zygentoma, Lepidotrichidae): morphology, ultrastructure and phylogenetic implications. Pedobiologia 48: 477 - 485." type="journal article" year="2004">SZKLARZEWICZ et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="42087E3EFF9A214FFF6A86AB40ECFB8D" blockId="2.[151,1127,219,1588]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">
A possible sister group relationship between 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFD6E86AA4134FD2A" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[689,849,733,756]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFD6E86AA4134FD2A" box="[689,849,733,756]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Euzygentoma + Pterygota has been raised by 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFE0A868B40FBFCCA" author="KRISTENSEN N. P." box="[469,670,764,788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="135 - 157" refId="ref9418" refString="KRISTENSEN N. P. 1981: Phylogeny of insect orders. Annual Review of Entomology 26: 135 - 157." type="journal article" year="1981">KRISTENSEN (1981)</bibRefCitation>
, based on the retention of the intergnathal connective ligament in the 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFE1B876C4000FCED" box="[452,613,795,819]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Archaeognatha" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Archaeognatha</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFD40876A4159FCEA" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[671,828,797,820]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFD40876A4159FCEA" box="[671,828,797,820]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A detailed analysis of the mandibles and mandibular musculature also corroborated the view that 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFC43874A465CFC8A" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[924,1081,829,852]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFC43874A465CFC8A" box="[924,1081,829,852]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a basal dicondylian (
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFEBD872B4068FCAA" author="STANICZEK A. H." box="[354,525,860,884]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="147 - 178" refId="ref10209" refString="STANICZEK A. H. 2000: The mandible of silverfish (Insecta: Zygentoma) and mayflies (Ephemeroptera): its morphology and phylogenetic significance. Zoologischer Anzeiger 239: 147 - 178." type="journal article" year="2000">STANICZEK 2000</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFDC1872B4172FCAA" author="BITSCH C. &amp; BITSCH J." box="[542,791,860,884]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="339 - 363" refId="ref7960" refString="BITSCH C. &amp; BITSCH J. 1998: Internal anatomy and phylogenetic relationships among apterygote insect clades (Hexapoda). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France 34: 339 - 363." type="journal article" year="1998">BITSCH &amp; BITSCH (1998</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFCFD872B413FFCAA" author="BITSCH C. &amp; BITSCH J." box="[802,858,860,884]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="131 - 156" refId="ref7995" refString="BITSCH C. &amp; BITSCH J. 2000: The phylogenetic interrelationships of the higher taxa of apterygote hexapods. Zoologica Scripta 29: 131 - 156." type="journal article" year="2000">2000</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFCBB872B41FEFCAA" author="BITSCH C. &amp; BITSCH J." box="[868,923,860,884]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="511 - 550" refId="ref8023" refString="BITSCH C. &amp; BITSCH J. 2004: Phylogenetic relationships of basal hexapods among the mandibulate arthropods: a cladistic analysis based on comparative morphological characters. Zoologica Scripta 33: 511 - 550." type="journal article" year="2004">2004</bibRefCitation>
) in their numerical analyses of morphological characters did not find any resolution of the representatives of the 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFF4887EB4375FC6A" box="[151,272,924,948]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Zygentoma</taxonomicName>
and of the Pterygota. 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFE2387EB4096FC6A" author="BEUTEL R. G. &amp; GORB S. N." box="[508,755,924,948]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="177 - 207" refId="ref7719" refString="BEUTEL R. G. &amp; GORB S. N. 2001: Ultrastructure of attachment specializations of hexapods (Arthropoda): evolutionary patterns inferred from a revised ordinal phylogeny. Journal of Zoological Systematics and Evolutionary Research 39: 177 - 207." type="journal article" year="2001">BEUTEL &amp; GORB (2001)</bibRefCitation>
performed a numerical analysis of 115 morphological characters and concluded that 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFD7987CA4126FC0A" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[678,835,957,980]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFD7987CA4126FC0A" box="[678,835,957,980]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents a sister group of the Euzygentoma-Pterygota clade, the latter supported by a reduced size of the postocciput and reduced pleural folds, reduced ligamentous head endoskeleton, reduced transverse mandibular apodeme, presence of 
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFE5E806A4172FBEA" box="[385,791,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">musculus mandibulo-hypopharyngalis</emphasis>
, shortened maxillary palps, and reduced or absent pregenital vesicles and styli.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0AAD2DB5FF9A214EFF6A802B464AFE0C" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="220" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" type="description">
<paragraph id="42087E3EFF9A214EFF6A802B43B1FF2C" blockId="2.[151,1127,219,1588]" lastBlockId="3.[113,1089,218,466]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="220" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">
In molecular analyses, the position of 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFD8E802A408BFBAA" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[593,750,1117,1140]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFD8E802A408BFBAA" box="[593,750,1117,1140]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was highly unstable, ranging from conventional placement as a sister group of the Euzygentoma (
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFCF1800B419FFB4A" author="MISOF B. &amp; NIEHUIS O. &amp; BISCHOFF I. &amp; RICKERT A. &amp; ERPENBECK D. &amp; STANICZEK A." box="[814,1018,1147,1172]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="409 - 429" refId="ref9784" refString="MISOF B., NIEHUIS O., BISCHOFF I., RICKERT A., ERPENBECK D. &amp; STANICZEK A. 2007: Towards an 18 S phylogeny of hexapods: accounting for group-specific character covariance in optimized mixed nucleotide / doublet models. Zoology 110: 409 - 429." type="journal article" year="2007">MISOF et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
: 18S ribosomal DNA) to an unorthodox intra-pterygote position next to the Odonata (
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFC0380EB4607FB6A" author="KJER K. M." box="[988,1122,1180,1204]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="506 - 514" refId="ref9158" refString="KJER K. M. 2004: Aligned 18 S and insect phylogeny. Systematic Biology 53: 506 - 514." type="journal article" year="2004">KJER (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, using the same molecular marker). Mitochondrial genomes have not yet been conclusive, evidently owing to poor taxon sampling, but they seem to support zygentoman monophyly (see 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFF17808B431CFACD" author="COOK C. E. &amp; YUE Q. &amp; AKAM M." box="[200,377,1275,1300]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="1295 - 1304" refId="ref8193" refString="COOK C. E., YUE Q. &amp; AKAM M. 2005: Mitochondrial genomes suggest that hexapods and crustaceans are mutually paraphyletic. Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences 272: 1295 - 1304." type="journal article" year="2005">COOK et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFE5C808B4038FACD" author="CAMERON S. L. &amp; BECKENBACH A. T. &amp; DOWTON M. &amp; WHITING M. F." box="[387,605,1275,1300]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="27 - 34" refId="ref8114" refString="CAMERON S. L., BECKENBACH A. T., DOWTON M. &amp; WHITING M. F. 2006: Evidence from mitochondrial genomics on interordinal relationships in insects. Arthropod Systematics &amp; Phylogeny 64: 27 - 34." type="journal article" year="2006">CAMERON et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFDB8808B4129FACD" author="CARAPELLI A. &amp; NARDI F. &amp; DALLAI R. &amp; FRATI F." box="[615,844,1275,1300]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="191 - 204" refId="ref8157" refString="CARAPELLI A., NARDI F., DALLAI R. &amp; FRATI F. 2006: A review of molecular data for the phylogeny of basal hexapods. Pedobiologia 50: 191 - 204." type="journal article" year="2006">CARAPELLI et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFC82808B4657FACA" author="GIRIBET G. &amp; EDGECOMBE G. D. &amp; CARPENTER J. M. &amp; D'HAESE C. A. &amp; WHEELER W. C." box="[861,1074,1275,1300]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="319 - 340" refId="ref8610" refString="GIRIBET G., EDGECOMBE G. D., CARPENTER J. M., D'HAESE C. A. &amp; WHEELER W. C. 2004: Is Ellipura monophyletic? A combined analysis of basal hexapod relationships with emphasis on the origin of insects. Organisms Diversity &amp; Evolution 4: 319 - 340." type="journal article" year="2004">GIRIBET et al. (2004)</bibRefCitation>
analyzed relationships among basal hexapods on the basis of a cladistic analysis of five genes and 189 morphological characters in a simultaneous analysis. Morphological characters solely corroborated monophyletic 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFE62812B4053FAAA" box="[445,566,1372,1396]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Zygentoma</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFD9A812A4087FAAA" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[581,738,1373,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFD9A812A4087FAAA" box="[581,738,1373,1396]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. Euzygentoma) but with very low support; the same applied to the multigene molecular analysis. Using a sensitivity analysis approach and testing for stability within the combined morphological-molecular analysis, the most congruent parameters resolved 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFD8D81CA408AFA0A" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[594,751,1469,1492]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFD8D81CA408AFA0A" box="[594,751,1469,1492]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a sister group to the remaining Dicondylia (with very low support again), whereas most suboptimal parameter sets grouped 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFF48818A4356F9CA" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[151,307,1533,1556]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFF48818A4356F9CA" box="[151,307,1533,1556]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the Euzygentoma. Finally, in the combined analysis by 
<bibRefCitation id="262603CFFF9A214FFC74818B4606F9CD" author="KJER K. M. &amp; CARLE F. L. &amp; LITMAN J. &amp; WARE J." box="[939,1123,1531,1555]" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" pagination="35 - 44" refId="ref9180" refString="KJER K. M., CARLE F. L., LITMAN J. &amp; WARE J. 2006: A molecular phylogeny of Hexapoda. Arthropod Systematics &amp; Phylogeny 64: 35 - 44." type="journal article" year="2006">KJER et al. (2006)</bibRefCitation>
, using eight gene sequences and 170 morphological characters, 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9A214FFCEB826A41B4F9EA" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[820,977,1565,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9A214FFCEB826A41B4F9EA" box="[820,977,1565,1588]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="219">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appeared as a sister group of the Euzygentoma.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="42087E3EFF9B214EFF4F848D464AFE0C" blockId="3.[113,1089,218,466]" pageId="3" pageNumber="220">
The position of the enigmatic 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9B214EFE18848C4001FECC" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[455,612,251,274]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="3" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9B214EFE18848C4001FECC" box="[455,612,251,274]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="220">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains controversial as none of the data sets provides substantial support for either of the two competing hypotheses (i.e. monophyletic or paraphyletic 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9B214EFEC8854D43F3FE8C" box="[279,406,314,338]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="3" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Zygentoma</taxonomicName>
). It seems only clear that a sister-group relationship between 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9B214EFBC6854C428AFEAC" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="3" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9B214EFBC6854C428AFEAC" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="220">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9B214EFE93852D43ABFEAC" authorityName="Escherich" authorityYear="1905" box="[332,462,346,370]" class="Insecta" family="Nicoletiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="3" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Nicoletiidae</taxonomicName>
has not yet been supported by morphology and molecular analyses. By all means, 
<taxonomicName id="85B705BDFF9B214EFEB8850C4067FE4C" authorityName="Wygodzinsky" authorityYear="1961" box="[359,514,379,402]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidotrichidae" genus="Tricholepidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Zygentoma" pageId="3" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70C3A22CFF9B214EFEB8850C4067FE4C" box="[359,514,379,402]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="220">Tricholepidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most promising candidate for a new insect ‘order’ (or, in other words, the only insect species whose ordinal classification remains uncertain), either as a sister group of the Euzygentoma, or of the Euzygentoma-Pterygota superclade.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
